# Implementation Discipline

## Surgical editing

- The diff should read as if the original author added the feature themselves: same style, same idioms, same structure.
- Touch ONLY lines required by the task. Reformatting, import reordering, or renaming unrelated code pollutes the diff and hides the real change. (Exception: your edit triggers the project's auto-formatter — that's fine.)
- One logical change per turn when possible. If the user asked for A and you discovered prerequisite B, do B, state why, then A — don't silently bundle C, D, E.

## Ordering that keeps the build green

Edit in dependency order so the project compiles at every checkpoint:
1. Types / interfaces / schemas
2. Core implementation
3. Call sites (find ALL of them — grep the symbol, don't trust memory)
4. Tests
5. Docs/comments if behavior described anywhere changed

After EVERY file edit: re-read your own diff for that file before moving on. Catching your own typo now costs 5 seconds; catching it after a failed build costs a full loop.

## Reuse before writing

Before writing any utility/helper/component, spend 20 seconds searching whether it exists:
- date/string/array helpers → search `utils/`, `lib/`, `helpers/`
- UI element → search `components/` for similar names
- API call → search for an existing client/service layer for that resource

Duplicating an existing utility is a bug: two implementations will drift.

## Completeness — the "80% done" trap

A weaker agent's signature failure: implementing the happy path and stopping. Before considering implementation finished, walk this list:

- [ ] All code paths handled: what happens on `null`, empty list, duplicate, concurrent call, thrown error?
- [ ] Every caller of changed functions updated (grep, don't assume)
- [ ] Errors surfaced properly (typed error / status code / user message per project convention), not swallowed
- [ ] No leftovers: `console.log`/`print` debugging, commented-out code, `TODO` placeholders, unused imports, dead variables
- [ ] New strings user-facing? → check if project has i18n; use it
- [ ] New env var/config introduced? → added to `.env.example` / config schema / README
- [ ] Feature reachable: route registered, component actually rendered, migration actually included — not just defined

"You can implement the rest similarly" is forbidden. Finish it.

## Editing safety

- Never overwrite a file wholesale when a targeted edit works — full rewrites silently delete code you didn't re-emit.
- When moving code between files, verify the destination compiles AND the source no longer references the moved symbol.
- Generated files (lockfiles, `*.gen.ts`, migrations already applied, build output): don't hand-edit; regenerate through the proper tool.
- If an edit tool fails or applies wrongly, RE-READ the file's current state before retrying. Never stack edits on a stale mental image of the file.
